notes: It was clear early on Sue Bird was destined for stardome, even before she made it to the WNBA. After winning the New York State Player of the Year award in high school, Bird went on to win two NCAA championships at UCONN, while tallying a staggering 114-4 record with the Huskies. In 2002, the Storm selected Bird first overal in the WNBA draft to pair alongside Lauren Jackson, who was selected first overall the year prior.

Bird put up a career high 33 points against the Portland Fire and broke a tie-breaker with the Fire for a Western Conference playoff berth. "This was a big game and everyone knew it," Bird said after the game.

Bird put the league on notice her rookie season, averaging 14.4 points per game and earning a spot on the Western Conference All-Star team. She was runner-up for the Rookie of the Year award and the duo of Bird and Jackson helped lead the Storm to playoffs for the first time, where Seattle was swept by the Sparks.

Bird became the fifth player in WNBA history to score 20 or more points and dish out 10 assists in a game in a win over the Mystics. "If she couldn't get to the basket, she was getting to the
foul line," Seattle coach Ann Donavoan told the AP after the game. "If she wasn't getting to the foul line, she was making
incredible assists."

In her second season, Bird averaged 12.4 points and 6.5 assists per game, leading the Storm in minutes played, three-pointers and steals. She was selected to her second All-Star game alongside Jackson, who won the league's MVP award. The Storm, however, had a disappointing season and missed the playoffs.

Bird's spinning reverse layup with 2.6 seconds left in overtime clinched an 85-83 victory over the Mystics, capping a 16-point comeback game by Seattle. "She made the most incredible shot I've ever seen in women's basketball," said Lauren Jackson after the game.

Bird added more hardware by claiming Olympic Gold in her first Olympic games with USA Basketball in Athens. Bird also became one of 11 women to win Olympic Gold, an NCAA championship and a WNBA championship.

After finishing the season with a franchise-best 20-14 record, the Storm tore through the playoffs and took down the Connecticut Sun in the Finals to capture their first WNBA Championship. Bird averaged 8.5 points and 5.3 assists per game throughout the playoffs, while Betty Lennox captured Finals MVP in her first season with Seattle.

Behind Bird's 12.1 points and 5.9 assists per game, the Storm again coasted to the playoffs, but were ousted in the first round by Houston. Bird led the leage in assists for the first time in her career in 2005.
Bird notched a swiped a career-high 7 steals in the Storm's season-opening win against the Sparks.

Bird set the WNBA record for three-pointers in a half with 6 during a scorching start against the Shock. Bird had 20 points in the half. "I don't think I've ever had a half like that in the pros," she said after the 81-79 win.
Bird became the fifth player to reach 1,000 career assists and the youngest in WNBA history. She finished with 11 points and 4 assists in the Storm's blowout win over New York.

With Jackson, the WNBA's reigning MVP, sidelined for the remainder of the season, Bird was forced into a scoring role for the Storm. After being asked to be a distributor for much of her career, Bird shouldered the load, averaging a career-high 19.7 points per game in 2008, including a 22-point effort in a win over Houston -- part of a four-game streak of 20 or more points for the point guard.

The Storm were the lone bright spot in an otherwise dreary year for Seattle sports in 2008. The Sonics played their last games in Seattle, the Mariners finishing with 101 losses and the Seahawks going 4-12, but the Storm finished second in the Western Confernce with a 22-12 record and went 16-1 at home. Bird had a career year, finishing third in MVP voting and leading the Storm in points (465) and assists (169). The Storm went on to lose to the Sparks in the first round of the playoffs.

The Storm again finished second in the Western Confernce with a 20-14 record, but for the fifth striaght yaer, Seattle couldn't get past the first round of the playoffs. Bird led the league in assists once again.

Bird and the Storm finally broke out in 2010, rolling to a franchise-best 28-6 record in the regular season, including an undefeated 17-0 record at home. And after years of frustrating early exists in the playoffs, the Storm breazed through the postseason with a perfect 7-0 record, capped by a sweep of the Atlanta Dream to clinch a second WNBA championship. Bird posted a career high 7.7 assists per game throughout the season, dishing many of them to Jackson, who won MVP for her third time.

Bird added another clutch moment to her resume, draining a 3-pointer with 0.4 seconds left to take down the Connecticut Sun 81-79. "In Sue Bird we trust," teammate Swin Cash told the AP after the game. "She's proven herself over and over again. When she puts that shot up, it's going in."

Bird underwent surgergy on her left knee and would miss the entire 2019 season as a result. She also missed the 2013 season with a left knee injury. While off the court, she impacted the WNBA in bigger ways. As a member of the WNBA Players Associated executive committee, Bird helped negotiate a "historic" labor agreement that would restrutcure the financial landscape of women's basketball. The deal represents moving forward both from a WNBA perspective, but also in general, for women in sports and society," she told The Times.
